The characters before the first space that you type in the Terminal
specify the command to run, the rest are information for that command
called arguments.
%
Use `download $SONG_ID [...]` to download one or more songs from YouTube.
%
Use `disu` to keep the computer from sleeping.
%
Use `fix ./path/to/song [...]` to attempt to fix one or more songs.
%
Use `cd /path/to/go/to` to go to another directory on the computer in
your Terminal.
%
A path that starts with `/` is started in the `Macintosh HD` directory.
%
A path that starts with `~` is started in your home directory.
%
You can drag files or directories into the Terminal to put their path into
a command.
%
Use `up [$NUMBER]` to go up that many directories from the current
directory. The default if no number is given is 1.
%
Use `pwd` to print the full path of the current directory you are in.
%
The Terminal will print the name for the directory you are in, at the
start of the line, this is called the prompt. It occasionally includes
additional info.
%
Use `ls [$PATTERN]` to list stuff found by the pattern. The pattern can be
used for filtering or searching other directories/paths. The default when
no pattern is given is to list the contents of the current directory.
%
Use `say your message here` to have the computer speak a message.
%
Use `echo your message here` to have the Terminal print that text.
%
Use `turtle` to see me again!
%
Use `cat ./path/to/text/file.txt` to have the Terminal print the contents
of the specified file.
%
Use `jobs` to list commands you have paused.
%
Press enter/return after typing a command to run it.
%
The `&` character marks the end of the preceeding command and arguments,
and says to run it in the background when you hit enter. A new command can
be typed after the `&`.
%
The `;` character marks the end the preceeding command and arguments. A
new command can be typed after the `;`.
%
The `$` character means the following characters up to the next space or
`/` are part of a variable name, replace them with the contents of the
variable.
%
The `?` character means try to find a file matching the rest of the
characters around the `?`, replacing one character where the `?` is.
%
The `*` character means try to find a file matching the rest of the
characters around the `*`, replacing zero or more characters where the `*`
is.
%
The `\` character means don't use the special meaning of the next
character.
%
The `/` character separates directory names in paths.
%
The `|` character means take the output of the command on the left of the
`|` and send it into the command on the right of the `|`, but not as
arguments unless you use `|xargs`.
%
A single `>` character means take the output of the command on the left of
the `>` and send it into the file on the right of the `>`, the file will
be emptied first before the command is run.
%
In a command `>>` means take the output of the command on the left of the
`>>` and append it to the file on the right of the `>>`.
%
In a path, a single `.` character means the current directory.
%
In a path, `..` means the parent directory of the one current directory.
%
The space character separates commands and the information you pass to
them.
%
The `!` character means lookup a previously run command using the
characters after the `!`.
%
Press control+c to quit a running program in the Terminal. A command that
is handling multiple arguments may need to be quit multiple times.
%
Press control+z to pause a running program in the Terminal. A command that
is handling multiple arguments may advance to the next argument.
%
Press control+a to go to the beginning of the line.
%
Press control+e to go to the end of the line.
%
Press control+k to cut everything from the cursor to the end of the line.
%
Press control+u to cut everything from the cursor to the beginning of the
line.
%
Press control+w to cut the next/rest-of-the word after the cursor.
%
Press option+w to cut the previous/rest-of-the word before the cursor.
%
Press control+y to paste the last thing you cut in the Terminal.
%
Press control+t to swap the characters on each side of the cursor.
%
Press option+t to swap the words on each side of the cursor.
%
Press tab to ask the Terminal to try to fill in the next part of the
command.
%
Hold option and click a place in the line to jump there.
%
Hello Jenn!
%
I'm a turtle!
